+The mounted `Testing` folder enforces **no-delete / no-overwrite-via-unlink** semantics (files can be rewritten in place and renamed, but not `unlink`ed) — consistent with the platform rule "files in Testing cannot be deleted or renamed once written." This breaks git's normal lock-file lifecycle (`index.lock`, `HEAD.lock`, `objects/*/tmp_obj_*`), which relies on being able to remove temp files after a rename. Symptom: `git init` / `git add` / `git commit` emit many `warning: unable to unlink ...: Operation not permitted` lines, and can leave a stale `index.lock` that blocks the *next* git command with `fatal: Unable to create '.git/index.lock': File exists.`
+
+**Same restriction was also observed in the session's own scratch `outputs/` sandbox directory** (not just the user-visible Testing mount) — this is a property of this Cowork sandbox's filesystem layer, not specific to the shared folder.
+
+**Workaround used:** git commands still function correctly *if* any stale `index.lock`/`HEAD.lock` left over from a previous command is renamed out of the way (`mv .git/index.lock .git/index.lock.stale.<ts>`) immediately before the next git command. Renames succeed even though deletes don't. Commits made this way are structurally valid (verified with `git fsck` — clean, and `git diff <base> <head> --stat` shows the expected file list).
